---
import "../styles/main.css"
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro"
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro"
import ThemeInit from "../components/ThemeInit.astro"
---
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en" class="scroll-smooth">
<head><meta charset="UTF-8" /><ThemeInit /><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
<title>Learn French with Flashcards - Free App with TTS Pronunciation</title>
<meta name="description" content="Learn French vocabulary with free flashcards featuring TTS pronunciation and spaced repetition. Start with our French Basics deck. No account required." />
<link rel="canonical" href="https://fluentcards.org/learn-french/" />
<meta property="og:title" content="Learn French with Flashcards - Free App" />
<meta property="og:description" content="Free French flashcard app with TTS pronunciation and spaced repetition." />
<meta property="og:url" content="https://fluentcards.org/learn-french/" />
<meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />
<script type="application/ld+json">{ "@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "WebPage", "name": "Learn French with Flashcards", "url": "https://fluentcards.org/learn-french/" }</script>
<script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-4482389932723468" crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
</head>
<body class="font-sans text-slate-700 bg-white dark:bg-surface-dark dark:text-slate-400 antialiased overflow-x-hidden">
<Nav currentPath="/learn-french/" />
<main class="pt-32 pb-16 px-6">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center reveal-up">
    <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100">Learn French with Flashcards</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-500 max-w-2xl mx-auto">Build your French vocabulary with smart flashcards featuring TTS pronunciation, FSRS spaced repetition, and a free French Basics deck. No account needed, works in your browser.</p>
    <a href="/app/" class="mt-8 inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-primary text-white px-8 py-3.5 rounded-xl font-bold shadow-lg shadow-primary/25 hover:shadow-xl transition-all">Start Learning French Free</a>
  </div>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto mt-16 space-y-8">
    <div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-surface-card rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 reveal-up">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200 mb-3">French Basics Deck</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">FluentCards includes a free French Basics deck with 35 essential vocabulary words covering greetings, common verbs, numbers, and everyday phrases. Each card includes the French spelling, English translation, and TTS audio for correct pronunciation. The deck is designed for absolute beginners. Clone the deck in one click and begin your first review session immediately with no account required.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-surface-card rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 reveal-up delay-1">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200 mb-3">French Pronunciation with TTS</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">French pronunciation can be challenging due to nasal vowels, silent letters, and the guttural R sound. Hearing correct pronunciation from native speakers is essential. FluentCards uses Microsoft Edge TTS to provide natural French pronunciation for every card. You can adjust the speech rate and practice shadowing by repeating the audio aloud. This technique trains your mouth muscles to produce French sounds correctly and helps develop a natural-sounding accent over time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-surface-card rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 reveal-up delay-2">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200 mb-3">Spaced Repetition for French</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">The FSRS spaced repetition algorithm in FluentCards automatically schedules reviews at optimal intervals based on your individual performance. Words you find difficult appear more frequently, while words you know well appear less often. This adaptive approach reduces total study time while significantly improving long-term retention. For French learners, this means you maintain a growing vocabulary without the constant review burden of traditional methods.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-surface-card rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 reveal-up delay-3">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200 mb-3">Tips for Learning French</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">French shares a large amount of vocabulary with English due to their shared history. This gives English speakers a head start of thousands of cognate words. Focus on mastering French pronunciation early, particularly the vowel sounds and the liaison rules that connect words in speech. Create sentence cards in FluentCards that show full French sentences on the front with translations on the back. This helps you internalize word order, gender agreement, and verb conjugation patterns naturally through repeated exposure.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

<h2>Getting Started with French</h2>
<p>FluentCards makes it easy to start learning French. When you open the app, you can immediately access the French Basics starter deck with 35 essential vocabulary words. Each card includes the French word, English translation, and TTS audio. The FSRS spaced repetition algorithm automatically schedules your reviews for maximum efficiency. Words you find difficult appear more frequently, while words you know fade into the background.</p>
<h2>Pronunciation and Listening</h2>
<p>FluentCards includes built-in TTS pronunciation that lets you hear each French word spoken naturally. Listen and repeat aloud to practice your pronunciation. Adjust the speech rate from slow to natural speed. Combine flashcard study with real-world exposure to French through podcasts, videos, and conversations for the fastest results.</p>
<h2>Building Your Vocabulary</h2>
<p>Study 15 to 20 minutes daily. Review all due cards and add 5 to 10 new words. At this pace you can learn over 1,000 words in three months. The streak tracker helps maintain momentum, and the FSRS algorithm ensures retention through optimally scheduled reviews.</p>

<p>French Basics starter deck gives you 35 essential French words with English translations and TTS audio. French pronunciation requires mastering nasal vowels and liaison rules that connect words in speech. FluentCards provides all the tools you need to build French vocabulary efficiently through spaced repetition, active recall, and consistent daily practice. The FSRS algorithm adapts to your memory and schedules reviews at optimal intervals. Start with the starter deck and expand with your own cards as you encounter new words in your studies. Whether you are learning for travel, work, or personal enrichment, FluentCards helps you make steady progress toward your French goals.</p><p>Consistent daily practice is the key to language learning success. Study for 15 to 20 minutes each day, complete all due reviews, and add 5 to 10 new vocabulary items. The streak tracker keeps you motivated, and the progress statistics show your improvements over time. With FluentCards, you have a complete language learning system that works on any device, anywhere, without requiring an account or subscription.</p><p>The combination of flashcards, TTS pronunciation, and spaced repetition creates a powerful learning environment that addresses reading comprehension, listening comprehension, and speaking ability simultaneously. By integrating these elements into a single seamless application, FluentCards helps you learn French more efficiently than traditional methods allow.</p>
<p>French is spoken by over 300 million people across five continents and is an official language of international organizations including the United Nations and UNESCO. Learning French provides access to a rich cultural heritage of literature, film, and cuisine. French pronunciation requires mastering nasal vowels and the guttural R sound. FluentCards TTS feature provides accurate French pronunciation for every card, helping you develop correct pronunciation habits from the beginning.</p><p>French nouns have gender, which affects the articles and adjectives used with them. Always include the article with each noun when creating flashcards to reinforce gender naturally. For example, create cards as le livre not just livre. This small habit makes a significant difference in your ability to produce grammatically correct French sentences. The French Basics deck includes 35 essential words with articles included to start you on the right path.</p>
<p>French verb conjugation is similar in complexity to Spanish, with different endings for each person and tense. However, French pronunciation makes some distinctions that are invisible in writing. For example, the endings -e, -es, and -ent for regular er verbs are all pronounced the same way. This means that writing conjugation is easier than speaking it correctly. Use the FluentCards TTS feature to hear each conjugated form pronounced correctly, and practice repeating aloud to develop accurate spoken French. Creating cards that include full sentences rather than isolated verbs provides context that helps you remember which conjugation patterns to use in real conversations.</p>
<p>FluentCards provides all the tools you need for effective language learning: FSRS spaced repetition, TTS pronunciation in over twenty languages, furigana for Japanese, AI-powered mnemonics, detailed progress tracking, and a community marketplace for sharing decks. All features are completely free with no account required. Start learning today by visiting the app and choosing a starter deck for your target language. The combination of scientifically optimized scheduling, active recall practice, and consistent daily study creates the most efficient path to language fluency available. Your future fluent self will thank you for starting today.</p>
</main>
<Footer />
<script>const o=new IntersectionObserver(e=>{e.forEach(e=>{e.isIntersecting&&e.target.classList.add("visible")})},{threshold:.08});document.querySelectorAll(".reveal-up").forEach(e=>o.observe(e));</script>
</body>
</html>
